item.title: Wahlenbergia luteola
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Lots of plants flowering inside and outside of a burnt area. Flowers lacked yellow colouring on the underside of petals, usually a key feature of W. luteola, but the leaves are all opposite, a feature that separates luteola from communis.

item.title: Petrorhagia dubia
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: 3rd pic shows ID features. 1) Densely glandular-tomentose mid-stem between leaf nodes. 2) Leaf sheath twice as long as stem width. 3) Seed tuberculate, 1-1.3mm (0.5mm marks on ruler in pic).

item.title: Convolvulus angustissimus subsp. angustissimus
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: Distinctive leaves on this subspecies. I was once told they are sometimes seen growing with subsp. omnigracilis and they are obviously different when seen together. It is true. See also obs 7616.

item.title: Convolvulus angustissimus subsp. omnigracilis
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: omnigracilis means 'all bits' slender, referring to the thin lobes on all leaves.

item.title: Geranium sp. 3
item.dc:creator: russell
item.description: 1st pic shows blue-purple dehiscence lines on anthers. 2nd pic show broad lobed over-winter leaf (bottom - seems to have spreading hairs) & thin-dissected summer leaves (top left). Peduncle seems to have appressed hairs.

item.description: Camera doesn't show colour well, which was very deep pink, almost magenta. Leaves diamond-shaped in cross-section and 2mm wide making it var. australis.
